<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-864-900  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 864 900.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  Nov 7 1989 v3 n40 p76(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT MacWEEK Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Scanner use expected to grow by 36 percent in next year.andO;(electronic scanning devices)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ScanningMarket PenetrationTrendsI-O DevicesGrowth.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Number of installed scanners to rise. (graph)Scanner purchase plans of MacWEEK subscriber organizations (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Scanner use expected to grow by 36 percent in next yearandM;The number of installed scanners is projected to increase by 36 percent inthe next year and at an average compound annual growth rate of 26 percentbetween 1989 and 1993, according to projections made by BIS CAPInternational, a market research firm in Norwell, Mass.andM;One of the major reasons for this rapid growth in the use of scanners,according to CAP, is improved price/performance levels, driven particularlyby the lower cost of electrohotographic engines.andP;  Other factors includeincreased use of electronic document storage and retrieval instead of paperor micrographics, better scanner and optical character recognition software,and the proliferation of fax machines.andM;MacWEEK's own survey of its subscribers' purchase plans found that 48 percentof organizations have plans to buy black-and-white scanners within the nextyear.andP;  Thirty-nine percent of subscribers said they will personnally purchasean average of 3.9 color scanners each.andP;  Only 18 percent of organizations,however, have plans to buy color scanners.andO;</TEXT></DOC>